WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:01.915
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.415 --> 00:00:04.347
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.347 --> 00:00:05.796
[CLICKING]

00:00:12.570 --> 00:00:16.530
JONATHAN GRUBER: So let's
continue our discussion

00:00:16.530 --> 00:00:18.630
of welfare economics.

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:20.455
Just to review where
we are, the first set

00:00:20.455 --> 00:00:22.830
of lectures in the course were
about positive economics--

00:00:22.830 --> 00:00:26.790
about understanding where supply
and demand curves come from

00:00:26.790 --> 00:00:28.230
and what they mean.

00:00:28.230 --> 00:00:30.270
Now, last lecture,
we turned from

00:00:30.270 --> 00:00:33.000
positive to normative
economics and actually making

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.820
judgments about whether
things are good or bad.

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:38.655
And we introduced the concept
of welfare, economic welfare

00:00:38.655 --> 00:00:39.810
or well-being.

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:42.240
And we talked about
consumer surplus, which

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:45.180
is a measure of how well-off
consumers are made by a given

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:48.180
exchange of goods and services,
and producer surplus--

00:00:48.180 --> 00:00:50.160
how well-off produces are made.

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:53.280
We're going to start our lecture
by proving what's modestly

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:55.320
called the first fundamental
theorem of welfare

00:00:55.320 --> 00:01:00.840
economics, which is that
competition maximizes welfare.

00:01:05.230 --> 00:01:10.170
So this is basically taking
our positive economics

00:01:10.170 --> 00:01:12.830
and meeting our
normative economics.

00:01:12.830 --> 00:01:15.230
That is, we are going
to talk about how

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:16.880
the model we've
derived so far, which

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:19.280
is the equilibrium under
perfect competition,

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:21.830
happens to also be
the outcome that

00:01:21.830 --> 00:01:24.792
delivers the maximum
well-being to society.

00:01:24.792 --> 00:01:26.230
So let's step back.

00:01:26.230 --> 00:01:28.960
Well-being we called welfare.

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:30.850
How do we define the
well-being of society?

00:01:30.850 --> 00:01:34.180
Well, we're going to start
with a simple definition, which

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:37.590
is we're going to at least
say that social welfare--

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:40.140
social welfare, the total
welfare of society--

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:43.730
is simply consumer surplus
plus producer surplus.

00:01:43.730 --> 00:01:45.980
That is, we're not going to
put any different weights.

00:01:45.980 --> 00:01:48.230
We're not going to say we like
somebody better than another.

00:01:48.230 --> 00:01:49.813
We're just going to
say, look, surplus

00:01:49.813 --> 00:01:51.320
is produced by a transaction.

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:55.007
And we just care about the
total surplus that's produced.

00:01:55.007 --> 00:01:57.090
And later, we can come to
help you about consumers

00:01:57.090 --> 00:01:58.538
versus producers, and we will.

00:01:58.538 --> 00:02:01.080
But right now, let's just say
we care about the total surplus

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:03.100
that's produced for society.

00:02:03.100 --> 00:02:07.092
How much benefit is produced
by this transaction?

00:02:07.092 --> 00:02:09.050
Well, the benefits produced
by this transaction

00:02:09.050 --> 00:02:12.320
is going to be the surplus
generated for consumers

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:15.200
by that transaction and the
surplus generated for producers

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:16.640
by that transaction.

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:19.100
So our total measure
of social well-being

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:22.840
is going to be the sum of
consumer and producer surplus.

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:24.425
And we are going to prove--

00:02:24.425 --> 00:02:26.050
as I said, you don't
need to know this.

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:28.690
But in [INAUDIBLE] it's called
the first fundamental theorem

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:32.260
of welfare economics, which
is that under the assumptions

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:34.700
we've made-- which are many--

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:36.460
under the assumptions
we've made,

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:40.870
the competitive equilibrium
where supply equals demand

00:02:40.870 --> 00:02:45.150
is the point that
maximizes social welfare.

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:48.840
That is, the key insight is the
point that the market naturally

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:50.130
delivers.

00:02:50.130 --> 00:02:52.920
The equilibrium that's gained
by the market naturally

00:02:52.920 --> 00:02:55.710
happens to be the point
that also makes society

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:57.810
as well off as possible--

00:02:57.810 --> 00:03:01.660
a very profound result. That
is, the positive conclusion,

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:03.160
which is that supply
and demand will

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:05.440
meet at a certain
equilibrium, delivers

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:08.290
a normative conclusion,
which is that equilibrium

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:10.450
is the point which
maximizes social welfare.

00:03:13.170 --> 00:03:15.280
Now, the best way to see
this is just graphically.

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:16.405
So let's go to Figure 10-1.

00:03:18.710 --> 00:03:23.030
Figure 10-1 has supply
and demand curve.

00:03:23.030 --> 00:03:26.000
Once again, whether these
are curved or linear,

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.573
it's still the basic idea
of supply and demand curve.

00:03:28.573 --> 00:03:29.990
So curve, supply
and demand curve,

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:32.310
are things which are more
constant elasticity type

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:32.810
curves.

00:03:32.810 --> 00:03:37.440
But that doesn't really
affect the intuition.

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:41.100
We have here the triangles of
consumer surplus and producer

00:03:41.100 --> 00:03:41.620
surplus.

00:03:41.620 --> 00:03:44.560
So consumer surplus--
give me the letter.

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:46.590
Somebody raise their
hand and tell me

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:49.560
which letters on this diagram
correspond to consumer surplus,

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:50.820
and why.

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:52.882
Which areas denoted by
which letters correspond

00:03:52.882 --> 00:03:54.090
to consumer surplus, and why?

00:03:57.350 --> 00:03:57.850
Yeah?

00:03:57.850 --> 00:03:58.700
AUDIENCE: R and v.

00:03:58.700 --> 00:04:00.450
JONATHAN GRUBER: R and
v. And why is that?

00:04:00.450 --> 00:04:02.530
AUDIENCE: Because the price is--

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.760
it really [INAUDIBLE]
here in between the supply

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:06.718
and demand [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:06.718 --> 00:04:07.760
JONATHAN GRUBER: Exactly.

00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:09.178
Everything below
the demand curve

00:04:09.178 --> 00:04:10.720
and above the price
consumer surplus.

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:14.280
So, r plus v. So therefore,
what's producer surplus?

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:16.089
Same person.

00:04:16.089 --> 00:04:18.089
AUDIENCE: S, t, and u.

00:04:18.089 --> 00:04:21.253
JONATHAN GRUBER: S plus t
plus u is producer surplus.

00:04:21.253 --> 00:04:23.295
So, consumer surplus-- r
plus v. Producer surplus

00:04:23.295 --> 00:04:24.590
is s plus t plus u.

00:04:27.770 --> 00:04:30.920
You can see, those of you
who are graphically oriented,

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:34.520
can immediately see the
sum of those two triangles

00:04:34.520 --> 00:04:37.880
will be maximized at the
intersection of the curves

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:38.730
and nowhere else.

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:46.210
So for example, let's think
about the case where I say,

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:48.820
well, look, it's a shame
the price is that high.

00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:50.770
We ought to make
the price lower.

00:04:50.770 --> 00:04:51.775
Let's set a new price.

00:04:51.775 --> 00:04:54.828
So let's have the government
mandate a new price at P2.

00:04:54.828 --> 00:04:56.620
Suppose the government
intervenes and says,

00:04:56.620 --> 00:04:58.778
we're going to set
a price ceiling.

00:04:58.778 --> 00:05:00.820
We're going to say no one
can charge more than P2

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:01.890
for their product.

00:05:01.890 --> 00:05:03.430
And won't that be a good
thing because the consumers

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:04.222
will be better off?

00:05:04.222 --> 00:05:06.400
They'll pay lower prices.

00:05:06.400 --> 00:05:09.040
Well, what does that do?

00:05:09.040 --> 00:05:10.960
What does that do
to consumer surplus?

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:16.840
Well, consumer surplus used to
be r plus v. It instead becomes

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:20.670
r plus s, which is bigger.

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:22.230
Consumer surplus rises.

00:05:22.230 --> 00:05:31.010
You lose the triangle v, and
you gain the rectangle s.

00:05:31.010 --> 00:05:37.550
But the key point is
at the price P2, yeah,

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:40.190
that becomes the new
consumer surplus.

00:05:40.190 --> 00:05:44.120
The new producer
surplus is what?

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:47.180
At that price P2, what's
the new producer surplus?

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:49.070
Someone raise their
hand and tell me.

00:05:49.070 --> 00:05:50.260
Yeah?

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:51.640
It's t.

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:52.480
It drops to t.

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:57.880
Producers just get below the
price above the supply curve.

00:05:57.880 --> 00:06:02.670
So what has happened to
total social welfare?

00:06:02.670 --> 00:06:06.910
It has fallen by
the amount v plus u.

00:06:06.910 --> 00:06:11.530
Total social welfare
has fallen by v plus u.

00:06:11.530 --> 00:06:14.650
So in some sense, two
things have happened here.

00:06:14.650 --> 00:06:17.240
We've set this price.

00:06:17.240 --> 00:06:19.730
The first is a transfer.

00:06:19.730 --> 00:06:22.490
We have transferred
the rectangle

00:06:22.490 --> 00:06:26.280
s from producers to consumers.

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:28.290
s used to be part
of producer surplus.

00:06:28.290 --> 00:06:29.958
We're now giving
it to consumers.

00:06:29.958 --> 00:06:31.500
So first thing we
have is a transfer.

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:33.360
That was probably the
idea of this policy--

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:34.865
make consumers better off.

00:06:34.865 --> 00:06:36.240
So we transferred
what used to be

00:06:36.240 --> 00:06:37.490
producer surplus to consumers.

00:06:37.490 --> 00:06:38.975
That's the rectangle s.

00:06:38.975 --> 00:06:40.600
That's the first
thing that's happened.

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:46.310
So thing one that's
happened is a transfer of s.

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:48.260
But the second thing
that's happened

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:57.130
is we have created what we call
a deadweight loss of u plus v--

00:06:57.130 --> 00:07:00.570
a deadweight loss
of u plus v. DWL--

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:02.810
Deadweight Loss.

00:07:02.810 --> 00:07:04.490
What is a deadweight loss?

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:07.970
That is the net
reduction in welfare

00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:10.810
from trades that are not made.

00:07:10.810 --> 00:07:13.490
The deadweight loss-- this is a
key concept we'll come back to,

00:07:13.490 --> 00:07:16.460
and I'll expect you
know it in your sleep.

00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:21.170
It's that deadweight loss is the
net reduction in social welfare

00:07:21.170 --> 00:07:25.220
from trades that are not made.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:30.700
The intuition here is
that every trade that

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:33.910
makes at least one
party better off

00:07:33.910 --> 00:07:36.280
without making the
other party worse off

00:07:36.280 --> 00:07:38.490
is a good trade to do.

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:40.290
Under the assumption
we've made so far,

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:43.860
if you ever trade that increased
consumer surplus or producer

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:48.110
surplus or both, that's
a good thing to have.

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:48.750
Right?

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:51.780
If my daughter has any song she
wants to buy by Kendrick Lamar

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:53.330
that she values at
more than $1.00--

00:07:53.330 --> 00:07:54.570
she gets them for $1.00--

00:07:54.570 --> 00:07:57.445
anything which stops her from
buying those songs is bad.

00:07:57.445 --> 00:07:58.320
She's losing surplus.

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:03.950
So basically, the key point
is that deadweight loss

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:06.990
is an inefficiency.

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:09.600
We talked about how
competition leads

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:13.960
to maximally efficient
production through cost

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:15.010
minimization.

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:19.180
Competition also leads to
the maximum welfare outcome

00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:23.440
because that point is the point
which makes society best off,

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:27.940
defined as the sum of consumer
surplus plus producer surplus.

00:08:27.940 --> 00:08:30.370
But once again, I cannot
highlight enough the depth

00:08:30.370 --> 00:08:31.900
of this insight.

00:08:31.900 --> 00:08:35.505
That this point which before
today, you knew as the outcome.

00:08:35.505 --> 00:08:36.880
I showed you in
the first lecture

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:39.088
this is what happens when
you have supply and demand.

00:08:39.088 --> 00:08:41.620
You get to this equilibrium
that happens to be

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:44.550
the very best place to be.

00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:46.940
And that's why we call it the
first fundamental theorem.

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:49.190
It's very important.

00:08:49.190 --> 00:08:50.176
Yeah?

00:08:50.176 --> 00:08:52.140
AUDIENCE: But the idea
then of since we're

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:54.380
caring about social worth, even
though the consumers are better

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:56.710
off, there is not as many
trades because the consumers

00:08:56.710 --> 00:08:58.653
don't get as much out of it?

00:08:58.653 --> 00:09:00.320
JONATHAN GRUBER: I
want to come to that.

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:01.050
Let's talk about that.

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:03.008
Let's go to another
example to talk about that.

00:09:03.008 --> 00:09:04.400
Let's talk about interventions.

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:05.240
Let's do it.

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:06.940
Let's do an example.

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:08.690
That was just to teach
you the basic idea,

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:10.850
but let's go on to a
more explicit example

00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:12.607
of a government intervention.

00:09:12.607 --> 00:09:13.690
Actually, I'll do it here.

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:23.030
Let me do an explicit example
of a government intervention.

00:09:23.030 --> 00:09:24.447
And that will
address the question

00:09:24.447 --> 00:09:29.060
which was just asked because I
skipped over a key point, here.

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:32.420
I'm always not sure the right
order to teach these things.

00:09:32.420 --> 00:09:35.100
So let's take
example of a market.

00:09:35.100 --> 00:09:37.010
Let's consider the
market for gas.

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:40.250
So go to Figure 10-2.

00:09:40.250 --> 00:09:42.800
This is a market we talked about
before, the market for gas.

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:45.080
Imagine the market
for gas is initially

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:51.300
in equilibrium with supply
curve S1 and a demand curve D.

00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:55.680
And it's initially in
equilibrium at point little e1,

00:09:55.680 --> 00:09:59.960
with Q1 gallons of gas
being sold at a price P1.

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:02.510
That's initial equilibrium.

00:10:02.510 --> 00:10:06.645
Now, imagine that
there is an oil crisis

00:10:06.645 --> 00:10:08.520
because, for example,
the oil company decided

00:10:08.520 --> 00:10:09.610
it would be good
idea to drill eight

00:10:09.610 --> 00:10:11.050
miles underground horizontally.

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:13.240
And it busts, and
there are spills

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:14.770
everywhere--
something like that,

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:16.930
some random example like that.

00:10:16.930 --> 00:10:19.240
And there's a supply crisis.

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:21.580
What happens now is
suddenly, it gets

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:24.130
more expensive to produce gas.

00:10:24.130 --> 00:10:25.930
So the supply curve
shifts upwards--

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:28.250
we talked about this last time--

00:10:28.250 --> 00:10:30.463
leading us to a new
equilibrium at point E2.

00:10:30.463 --> 00:10:32.005
And you remember,
we talked about how

00:10:32.005 --> 00:10:32.930
the equilibrium works.

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:34.910
Initially, if we think
about it in steps,

00:10:34.910 --> 00:10:37.280
initially you've
created an excess demand

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:38.780
because gas companies
no longer want

00:10:38.780 --> 00:10:46.130
to supply Q1 gallons at a price
P1 from their new supply curve.

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:48.620
So you shift along
the demand curve

00:10:48.620 --> 00:10:52.020
to the new point E2, which
is a new equilibrium.

00:10:52.020 --> 00:10:53.730
And all is well and good.

00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:54.840
Prices go up.

00:10:54.840 --> 00:10:58.920
That's what happened after Deep
Water and things like that.

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:01.330
Now, imagine the government
doesn't like that.

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:03.630
Imagine the government says,
well, we don't like that.

00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:05.460
We don't like the fact consumers
have to pay more for gas.

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:06.960
Consumers vote us
out of office when

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:08.640
they have to pay more for gas.

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:11.820
So we are going to solve this
by imposing a price ceiling.

00:11:11.820 --> 00:11:13.560
We are going to announce
the price of gas

00:11:13.560 --> 00:11:16.215
must remain at its old level P1.

00:11:19.935 --> 00:11:21.060
So let's go to Figure 10-3.

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:27.058
Figure 10-3 shows what happens
when the government imposes

00:11:27.058 --> 00:11:27.850
that price ceiling.

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:33.340
Well, the first question
is if the government

00:11:33.340 --> 00:11:36.610
imposes a price ceiling
of P1, how much actually

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:37.780
gets sold in the market?

00:11:37.780 --> 00:11:40.580
This comes to the question
that was just asked.

00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:44.340
Well, this is sort of a
new thing we've looked at,

00:11:44.340 --> 00:11:47.060
which is we have the situation
where there's excess demand.

00:11:47.060 --> 00:11:52.390
At the price P1, consumers
still want Q little d.

00:11:52.390 --> 00:11:56.050
But suppliers are only willing
to supply Qs, Q little s.

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:56.890
See?

00:11:56.890 --> 00:12:00.450
Consumers still are working
off the same demand curve.

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:03.020
If the government says we
still want the price to be P1,

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:03.520
they're like, great.

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:05.312
We still want as much
gas as we had before.

00:12:05.312 --> 00:12:06.482
Supplies are like, no way.

00:12:06.482 --> 00:12:07.690
We're not going to supply it.

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:08.950
If you're going to keep
the price at that level,

00:12:08.950 --> 00:12:11.080
we're going to produce
less gas because we

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:12.560
have a rising marginal cost.

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:14.560
So if you're going to
force out that same price,

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:16.870
we're going to work our way
back down the supply curve

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:18.370
and produce less gas.

00:12:18.370 --> 00:12:22.660
So suddenly, you have a
situation of excess demand

00:12:22.660 --> 00:12:23.898
that doesn't get resolved.

